i accepted the situation as my own shortcoming. i was disappointed in what i thought was my lack of decency and control.

column2: i spent most of my day yesterday completely riveted by the testimony of dr. christine blasey ford to the senate judiciary committee. i expected that her testimony might make me a little emotional
column3: as listening to a woman recount the details of her own assault would inevitably do. i did not expect it to rip me wide open. iâ€™m a 26 year old canadian woman
column4: and although the implications of brett kavanaugh winning his nomination will not directly affect my life
column5: it will break my heart knowing that for millions and millions of other women
column7: will be knowing that it would cause survivors everywhere to affirm â€œthis is why i didnâ€™t report.â€ survivors like myself. i was raped at a party soon after my 16th birthday. i had been drinking heavily
column8: and to this day believe that i was drugged. i may have lost some inhibitions when i drank
column9: but this was the only time in my entire life that i lost my memories
column10: too. i first realized something had gone horribly wrong when i woke up in my bed the next morning
column11: in unfamiliar pain somewhere that pain is not normal. from there
column12: the night came back to me in pieces in the weeks after the assault. i remembered finding a bathroom to throw up in. i remembered throwing up in the sink while i washed my hands. i remembered uninvited hands exploring my body while i was hunched over
column13: trying to rinse out the mess i had made. what i remember the most clearly is how ashamed i was. the embarrassment that blanketed me. how dirty i had become. how i blamed myself. it was my fault for drinking too much. my fault for venturing away from my friends
column14: for not asking one of them to come with me. my fault for not locking the door behind me. it was my fault. it took me over 5 years to even admit to myself that i had been raped
column15: let alone to anyone else. i told my best friend first. then my boyfriend. i finally told my mom last year. i told my dad last week. column1: 332106;instagram;2018-09-28 12:38:21;FALSE;"in light of yesterdayâ€™s hearing we feel so many things and know that many of you out there may be experiencing retraumatization. if you need support you can call the national sexual assault hotline at 1-800-656-4673 or go to rainn.org.
we believe in using our voices to incite change in our world. we believe that all people should be safe from being violated and that their stories should be seen

column1: 332159;instagram;2018-09-28 12:56:32;FALSE;i canâ€™t even begin to describe how grateful i am for your messages and calls of solidarity/love this week. i wish every survivor could experience the overwhelming support i received. i never anticipated sharing my #metoo story (at all
column2: let alone publicly) but wanted to show other women that they are not alone and that their story matters regardless of how much time has passed. even though my assault was 14 yrs ago it doesnâ€™t make my story less valid
column3: less credible or less believable. the number of women/friends/family who reached out saying they havenâ€™t been able to publicly share their story yet would blow your mind. with their permission
column4: iâ€™ve listed a few of them anonymously (there were so many more). please read each and every one of them. it shows that we still have a long way to go. these strong incredible women are your friends
column8: coworkers. 1 in 3 is only what is reported but almost every women i know has a story. please vow to always support the women in your life. to help elevate their voice
column9: their equality and their demand for accountability against the â€œboys will be boysâ€ narrative. vocalize your solidarity. walk the walk. vow to make sure they know they will be believed if they ever choose to share their painful story and to stand beside them even if they donâ€™t. vow to educate the youth so we can help break the cycle as a parent
column12: coach or community leader. vow to elect officials who take sexual assault allegations seriously and who demand actual change/investigations. vow to intervene if you ever see or hear an assault. it takes a village but together

column1: 332189;instagram;2018-09-28 13:07:34;FALSE;i am a rape survivor whoâ€™s dad was falsely accused of molesting me by my mother so she could get custody of me in the 80â€™s. that year he was one of three fathers proven innocent out of three hundred accused in our city alone of molesting their children. it was popular in the 80â€™s to win custody and my motherâ€™s lawyer planted that idea in her head. dad was an education director at our church and also taught sunday school. before it even went to court she had told the whole church and everyone she could. he was kicked out of the church
column3: sc. he couldnâ€™t go anywhere without parents shielding their kids from him. he has had a hard time even walking in a church. it was my testimony at 6 years old that kept him from going to prison. i do believe ford but also kavanaugh. i think something did happen to ford. i donâ€™t think both parties have taken the right steps. i think it should not be for the media to sensationalize. i think people are deciding guilty until proven innocent. i think ford is brave and should be supported. from a rape survivor who did not report it because my coworkers (females) said i confused rape with regret to a mother who has never apologized and said she would accuse my father all over again i stand with all parties. i have a criminal justice degree and i believe in due process. the media has turned this into a circus. to my dad who faced prison time and possibly not coming out alive because we know what prisoners do to rapists and molesters

column1: will you let your anger stay as an overnight guest? for the weekend? as a traveling nomad who is always welcome at your door?
will you give your anger the room inside of you that it needs to expand
will you invite your anger to the dinner table?
or does that feel too daring?
will you open your mouth and let anger carve your tongue into words of disruption and assertion?
will you give anger a chance?
will you let her be a guide to you in these burning times?
does anger have a room of her own in your house?
do you keep space for her
column2: honoring that when she comes as a house guest
column3: she will always have a place?

column1: or do you kick her outside
column2: circling and racing the property like a ravenous dog?

column1: i donâ€™t know how long youâ€™ll need to sit with her.
it is different for all of us.
it might be one holy hour
she is part of the team.
i would suggest that she must be included if we are really serious about burning things to the ground.
humility. courage. compassion. resilience. love. trust. faith. hope. -
we need all these players in the room.
she is the very weapon that the patriarchy has programmed us to fear the most in ourselves.
anger is our ally. she is the great leveler and destroyer who must be called upon to help catalyze and digest the toxic debri that is floating in the very air we breathe.
for as long as you can.
until you know youâ€™re free and clear of the residue of fear
column3: and powerlessness that has been wrongfully imprinted onto your heart.

column1: the world will tremble when every woman howls with holy anger that is conjured from deep within the center of the earth; her womb.
that is the sound i will live and die praying to hear.

column2: 000 emotions today. just promise me this. promise me you will open your front door when anger knocks.

column1: 332240;instagram;2018-09-28 13:25:51;FALSE;"if you're questioning whether or not that thing that happened to you was assault
column2: you're not alone. this happened last year with #metoo and it's happening again now. as more survivors find the strength to stand up and share the story of the violence perpetrated against their bodies
column3: more of us are seeing our stories in theirs.

column1: this period of reckoning can be confusing. it was for me.

column2: i talked myself out of it. i was ashamed that it happened
column3: embarrassed that it happened to me
column4: and all i wanted after it happened was to escape. i didn't call the police. i didn't go to the hospital. i didn't tell anyone until i told my husband last year.

column1: i told myself that because i didn't fight back
column2: i must have wanted it. i didn't fight back because i didn't know how. i had to choose: if i fight back
column3: he might kill me. if i pretend to be sleeping
column4: i might survive. i pretended to sleep.

column1: i told myself that maybe my no wasn't firm enough the night before. or maybe consent (or the lack thereof) is an agreement that must be renewed at midnight. maybe i just didn't say no loud enough or firm enough or in the right way.
if you are a survivor and you are feeling all the feelings this week
column2: give this a listen when you want to feel a little less alone.

column1: 332249;instagram;2018-09-28 13:27:24;FALSE;"a strong feeling of hunger a few days before or during menstruation is a normal phenomenon for many women. it can be explained by a change in hormonal levels. there are two hormones that influence appetite:leptin (the higher itâ€™s level the taste you feel full) and ghrelin (when itâ€™s even goes up so does your appetite).

the level of the latter is affected by sleep quality. if you donâ€™t get enough sleep ( especially in the second phase of the cycle) the gherlin rises and the craving for food is more intense than it usually is. appetite also depends on insulin and cortisol (stress hormone) and even on sex hormones. .

a decreased estrogen level before menstruation can raise the level of ghrelin and low estradiol makes your mood go down. as a result your body asks for food because it is a way of increasing the amount of endorphins (happiness hormones). donâ€™t worry much about your elevated hunger.  this is only a temporary physiological state. #yamawomen #yamaconversations #pressforprogress #womenhistorymonth

column1: 332252;instagram;2018-09-28 13:27:48;FALSE;"sexual assault can happen in many different ways. i have shared my most traumatic story
column2: the story that i still think about and swallows me whole some days
column3: many times. it isn't my first story though. i thought i'd share it now because it makes a good case that you don't remember every detail and that you don't always talk about it.

column1: i want to say i was 9 years old
column2: but i could have been anywhere from 8 to 11. i was at the baseball field by the high school watching my dad play for the church team. a guy that i feel like was in his 30s but i really have no idea (though my dad may recall his name and age) was paying attention to me
column3: giving me baseball cards and he was challenged in a mental capacity in some way. we were walking behind the bleachers
column4: which is an open area along the street
column5: when he pushed me or pulled me down
column7: but he was on top of me
column8: trying to kiss me and i was panic giggling (a bad habit i still have) and struggling to get away from him. mrs. novak saw him and yelled at him to get away from me and then she made me sit next to her the rest of the game....and i remember feeling soooo grateful to her.

column1: that was at least 20 years ago. you don't always remember every little thing
column3: you remember how you got away....and even though this story wasn't nearly as traumatic...it sticks with you. i don't think i told but a few people that story ever until now. and only now to say that it doesn't make someone less credible that they don't remember the day of the week
column4: the month or even the year (like i don't)
column5: those aren't the things that stay with you. #believesurvivors

column1: i believe dr. ford. i believe because i know what it's like to grow up being socialized with male privilege. i know how men think about women . i know how men treat women. i know how men talk about women amongst each other.

many men wholesale objectify women. they think that they are an object to obtain. they are a conquest. they are a goal to achieve and brag about amongst your friends. many men think that is their place to judge a woman's appearance
even among people but i consider good men
column2: these traits exist. i cannot tell you how many times i've witnessed good men denigrate women
column5: talk about how they can and plan to pressure them into sex.

column1: many men are raised with the expectation that women will make false accusations. with this in mind
column2: it is easy to dismiss any woman who says that they were sexually harassed or assaulted as being a liar. i can tell you from the both sides how quickly men are prone to dismiss women
column3: try to dominate any interaction with them
column4: and look down on them as somehow inferior in all scenarios.

column3: that testosterone is a very powerful hormone. it is overwhelming in its ability to affect your behavior. it makes people aggressive. it makes them horny. it clouds your judgment. it is hard to adjust to when you are young and still maturing.

column4: make stupid f'ing decisions. this is bad enough on its own
column5: when you mix it with alcohol in a culture that tells you that you have the right to women's bodies it is a very dangerous combination.

column2: and based on seeing the coin from both sides
column3: dr. ford's testimony rings excruciatingly true and brett kavanaugh's cavalier angry performance is indicative of an overprivileged man raging that someone had the umbrage to bring him to task.

column1: you did the right thing by coming forward
column2: maybe you will not change the course of political carnage laid out in front of us. but it was the right thing
column3: i would like to tell you why.

column1: you did the right thing because there are a lot of women out there that have shared your story...different setting
column2: different person....but the same story. we heard your voice and you gave us ours back. you gave us permission to not keep all that hurt bottled up. you gave us a voice to say
column3: i did not deserve it. if you helped one women/girl (and i know you did because i am one of them) then you coming forward was not for nothing!

column1: you did the right thing because sometimes things need to fall apart to be build back stronger. i believe this is just the beginning of the truths that will come out over the years....but the lies are being brought to the surface. not necessarily just about our politicians
column2: but about the sex driven culture that has taken over our world. sex trafficking
column4: incest..we have had enough! this is just the beginning..

column1: you did the right thing because no one needs to hold that shit in. speak your truth! look at you
column2: you are a very accomplished woman and mother. you took what those boys did to you and you used that to fuel you. you did not give into the anxiety and pain
column3: you are an amazing example of the type of power the human spirit can contain.

column2: and i wanted to say thank you. i will share my story one day
column3: but what your voice helped me realize is i have a lot to work through. we are ever growing individuals. i have been in counseling more years of my life than not and i have never spoke of my night because i was an alcoholic. i always thought i deserved it. i had put myself in that situation and deserved it
column4: not true. i was not living my best life at the time and maybe if i had been i could have avoided the situation all together..but i do not play the â€œwhat ifâ€ game with myself. i look at it as a time period where i had to be broken in order to rise out of the ashes like the phoenix i am!

column1: boys will be boys""....this statement is often used to excuse inappropriate behavior exhibited by males. however
column3: this statement absolves boys/men from exhibiting self control and in turn breeds a sense of entitlement within our boys/men that leads to a lot of the predatory behaviors that we see. granted there are some predators who are sociopathic and we aren't going to curb their deviant desires. but for the rest of the male population
column4: we must drive home the concept of consent and self control early on. we cannot excuse unwanted  or inappropriate touching as ""boys will be boys"" because  1) we are sending a message to our girls that they have no control over their bodies

column1: 332396;instagram;2018-09-28 14:04:44;FALSE;"i could feel the shift of change!yesterday the world watched as a brave woman spoke her truth. it was her truth. no one else's. even through the the fear that was so blatantly obvious she spoke her truth. dr. ford was articulate
column2: and brave. her courage shinning through the nerves. this should not be ridiculed
column3: or doubted. she was not on trial. i understand as a survivor myself the courage it takes to break your silence
column4: and confront your attacker. she had to do this on the largest scale possible. in front of not only a panel of people tasked with the job of picking through her truth
column5: but the entire world. instead of propagating doubt. ask yourself
column6: could you do the same? if it were not her truth would the risk out weigh the reward of her doing her ""civic duty""? one of the hardest parts of telling your truth is the doubt. the backlash can make you begin to doubt yourself. for the victim/survivor there is no reward in reliving trauma on that scale. there is no political agenda worth putting oneself through that. i support dr. ford. not because of a political agenda. not because she is a fellow survivor
column7: or woman. not because this was done on such a grand scale. i support her because it was a courageous act that took immeasurable bravery. that is what the world should be doing. i stand with dr. ford
column8: and every other human being on this planet willing to make that kind of sacrifice. i stand with those able to tell their truth
column9: and those who suffer in silence. i want to say thank you to not just dr. ford but all survivors. you are not alone in this fight.

column1: georgia o'keefe has had a huge influence on me as a woman & her words have come to define everything i do in my work. she said
column2: 'the most important thing is to make the unknown known'. ++++++++++++++++++++ the process framework i created is used to help us identify when we're standing on the shore of our life merely replicating what we already know and when we're submerged in the ocean of our true selves where we are able to connect with all that is still yet to be known deep within us. ++++++++++++++++++ as a meaning maker
column3: everything i do is about uncovering that unknown within me so that i can make it known to myself and the world. +++++++++++++++++ it is the process of making our unknown known that transforms us from mere pawns in a consumer driven capitalist patriarchal society back into the creators that we all are. ++++++++++++++++ we come into this world and leave it through a creative act and in between the greatest contribution that any of us can make is to bring forth what is unknown within us. ++++++++++++++++ deep gratitude for all the women making their unknowns known so we can all experience the truth of who we are beyond the limitations that the world has placed upon us. ğŸ™ğŸ» +++++++++++++++++ #christineblaseyford #metoo #anitahill #whyididntreport #womenmustchangetheworld #meaningmaker #m2movement";;en;#christineblaseyford

332560;instagram;2018-09-28 14:41:06;FALSE;i know ig isn't a popular place for politics. but sometimes you have to speak up.

ms. ford is a hero for standing up and testifying against brett kavanaugh. she's endured harsh critique to the point that she's had to move out of her home because of harassment. she's talking about attempted rape.

i was 19 when i was having intercourse with someone and decided i wanted him to stop (it stopped feeling like the right thing to do). he didn't stop. it turned him on. i tried to get him off me but he pinned me down. so i let him finish because i thought i had to.

column2: i consider myself supremely lucky. it hasn't stopped me from trusting sexual partners. it just made me smarter.

column1: my point: i can't imagine sitting in front of a group of strangers
column3: just for them to question me and possibly not believe me.

column2: and please be concerned if he's confirmed for scotus. it will affect you as an american

column2: without having someone touch you unwantedly
column3: and most definitely without being sexually harassed or assaulted.

column4: ask for hannah on the door

column2: and will always endeavor to do as much as we can to make sure you are getting into a taxi safely and are able to get home- we'll always encourage you to travel with friends and will do our best to hand out water on the door.

column3: don't touch anyone inappropriately whether you know them or not
column4: and be vocal if you aren't happy with a situation. we promise to do as much as we possibly can to keep team up a rad place to party.

column1: 332694;instagram;2018-09-28 15:10:26;FALSE;"i'm pretty vocal about being a feminist. i think sometimes it makes people a little uncomfortable and annoyed.
well. i am uncomfortable and annoyed.
i am annoyed that my plain t shirts and razors and deodorant cost more than nate's.

column2: which i will have to keep buying every month til i'm 50

column1: i am annoyed that when i leave my house without spending 30 minutes shaving and 15 doing my makeup that i feel unhygenic and get told i look tired at least four times.
i am annoyed at the innumerable times i have been called bossy and the lack of times i have been told i am a good leader.
i am annoyed at how often i am interrupted and spoken over
column2: or argued with from a total other point than that of what i said.

column1: i am annoyed at cringing at things my male professors and classmates say in ignorance.
i am annoyed at bs dress codes and bs reasons for them.
i am annoyed that i will forever reasonably be scared of parking garages
i am annoyed that my shopping is forever dependent on when someone is able to go with me.
i am annoyed that i will forever be scared for my friends who do not have that sense of self preservation. i will never forget the scared call from my friend who was followed when she was so naive.
i am annoyed at how many of the girls i work with and my friends have been harassed
i am annoyed at how much sexual harassment i put up with in hs because i thought that was just reality and that's how boys flirt. i am annoyed i was advised that it was a compliment.
i am annoyed at seeing the government attack women's health rights and allow rape to go unpunished.
i am annoyed that the men who do notice these things make it about protecting themselves from allegations
column3: and make me feel like nothing but walking sexual temptation and not a person.

column1: i am annoyed. and i always will be until change starts to happen. so suck it up and try to hear me as i speak up for myself and those who have less of a voice than me.

column1: 332809;instagram;2018-09-28 15:36:37;FALSE;"i watched dr anita hill speak at ghc18 today.. and i have no words to describe this feeling.

if i ever have a daughter ... this is what i will say to you some day. ""things will happen to you because you are a girl. they are going to cause you to question who you are... i want you to know .. you can always come to me and tell me about those things. i want to know how your classmates are treating each other. i want to know how school was for you. i want to know if someone made you uncomfortable.

you are a beautiful girl. and i never want you to be afraid. have you ever had something happen to you.. that you didn't want to tell me because you thought people won't believe you? don't be afraid to ask that question.

the work we are doing to make a inclusive work force is worthy of all of our talents and energy. and i know it's hard. we are trying to change a culture and it's challenging. you may want to give up . and i understand that.. but just stay in there. work with others.. bring together the resources you have. never lose sight of the goal.. and always recognize the small advances that you make. acknowledge the small triumphs.
column2: it'll keep you focused on the goal.

column1: hang in there.. you are supported and we want you to succeed in. whatever you are contributing to the world.

column7: despite everything i was told while growing up. despite everything i was told after i grew up.

column1: i can honestly say that was one of the hardest decisions i've ever had to make but everyday following the incident i woke up with this little voice in my heart telling me that not only did i have to stand up and speak my truth for myself
column2: i had to do it for the countless other women who i knew he had done this to and would continue to do this to. see
column4: do things like that. men like that think that the rules don't apply to them because they have enough money to buy their way out of any situation. men like that are predators and it's my belief that the general public has a right to know who the predators are among them. the process that i went through was long and difficult. telling my story to a room full of people who were there to disprove me was an experience i will never forget. it took a level of courage i didn't know i had
column5: but i did it and in the end he was found guilty and i knew i had done the right thing. telling your story is the only way to begin healing the trauma of sexual abuse and sexual assault. many go their whole lives without telling a single soul what happened to them. my heart breaks for those that carry the burden and the weight in silence. after watching dr. christine blasey ford's testimony all i can think of is how grateful i am that she listened to the little voice in her heart and found the courage that she probably didn't know she had to do what she did yesterday. dr. ford
column6: thank you for sharing your story. thank you for your courage. thank you for your strength. your bravery has created a ripple effect that we cannot even fathom. you've given a voice to the silent and have inspired many to share their stories which can only bring healing.

column1: sending so much love out to all the #survivors this week. it's hard enough to live with the aftermath of sexual abuse and sexual assault but times like this can be extremely triggering and many have spent the week reliving their most painful memories. if you know a survivor
column2: reach out. let them know you're there if they need you. and if you are a survivor
column3: reach out. ask for help. you aren't alone.

column1: 332941;instagram;2018-09-28 16:00:36;FALSE;this week has me spinning. yesterday i couldn't be involved and yet i found myself checking the status to see how it was going and to see if she if she had gotten through to them. that small part of me that hopes this whole discussion is almost resolved instead of *still* just beginning because many men continue to refuse to start it. i marveled at her bravery and willingness to re-traumatize herself for the greater good knowing she would have to move through this wound and pain all.over.again. i felt powerless and i felt like all the work i've been doing to heal was for nothing. i took myself back to the last time i felt powerful and it was here
column2: with this giant waterfall that somehow awakened the power within me to finally believe that being assaulted was not my fault. it took me nearly a decade to believe this
column3: but once you believe you can never go back to where you were. there will be setbacks
column4: but the power of that belief will carry you forward. sending love to all my fellow survivors and wishing you peace in believing. yesterday was absolute trash
column5: but we will work through it and we will heal from it because we believe. nobody else's belief matters but your own. #metoo #drfordisahero  and for real thank to @beyonce for helping me work through my feelings last night. i laughed
column7: and i screamed with rage. thank you for creating the space and for continuing to hold down black women.;;en;#metoo

column1: 332958;instagram;2018-09-28 16:04:31;FALSE;"i believe survivors. i believe them. why shouldn't i? who am i to judge them? ..
i myself have been hurt. while in a relationship with this person they where on of the most absive people i have ever meet. at first
column2: i thought all the stories i was told were lies. i thought nothing of the warnings. to this day i still hate myself for that. at first glance
column4: but when you look deeper you could see the abuse. maybe not all physical
column5: but he blamed me when he cheated

column1: this why we don't speak up.
i never told how a boy named jeff held a knife to throat in elementary school...
he looked me right in my eyes and thought my terror was hilarious.
seconds later he retracts the knife and laughs...
however he was doing the same thing as a rape
i have lived through attempted rape. i have lived through rape...
ones i have never spoken about.
because i have even asked myself why i never fought harder
column2: even to the death. maybe i was too intoxicated
that young boy putting that knife to my neck is something that has stayed with me my entire life. it has shaped the fear i feel around men
column3: and why i am extremely careful (and distrusting). time doesn't take away the experience or how it has shaped us
column4: time just makes it easier to face it down.
